I had a great conversation with constituents at Black Diamond in Citrus County during my latest Coffee with Your Congressman event this week.  We discussed how the Working Families Tax Cuts are providing meaningful relief to Americans, and I appreciated hearing their thoughtful insights on how Congress can better support seniors and hardworking families.  Thank you to those who joined me — your voices matter.

It was wonderful to reconnect with my former colleague, Congresswoman Jennifer Wexton, at a recent event focused on Parkinson’s disease. Sadly, she was forced to retire earlier than she had hoped due to an aggressive form of this debilitating illness.  I assured her that we will continue the fight in Congress to accelerate the development of more effective treatments—and ultimately, a cure—for the millions of Americans impacted by Parkinson’s. Her strength and advocacy continue to inspire us all.

The Rural Healthcare Transformation Fund—signed into law as part of the One Big Beautiful Bill—is a game-changer.  I’m looking forward to seeing Florida’s application and how this landmark program will be utilized locally to strengthen rural hospitals and expand care for vulnerable patients throughout our community.

I was honored to receive the Hero Award from @BreakthroughT1D Children's Congress. As Co-Chair of the Diabetes Congressional Caucus, I remain committed to fighting for greater access to care and advancing federal support for research and better treatments for all those living with diabetes.

In a major step forward for America’s energy security, the House just passed H.R. 1047 – the GRID Power Act with my support.  With electricity demand surging due to AI, domestic manufacturing, and electrification, our grid must be ready. But outdated rules and Biden’s anti-energy agenda have caused delays, plant retirements, and blackout risks.  This bill cuts red tape and puts essential, reliable power projects at the front of the line—keeping the lights on and the economy moving. House Republicans are taking action to protect the grid and power America's future.   #GRIDPowerAct #EnergySecurity #CutTheRedTape

It was an immense blessing and a singular honor to welcome His All-Holiness Bartholomew Archbishop of Constantinople, New Rome, and Ecumenical Patriarch.   His All Holiness is the revered spiritual leader of 300,000,000 million Orthodox Christians worldwide and is the 273rdsuccessor of the founder of the Eastern Orthodox Church, St. Andrew the Apostle. I am grateful that Speaker Mike Johnson hosted His All Holiness for a luncheon in the U.S. Capitol today which underscores the importance of The Ecumenical Patriarch’s relevance as a spiritual leader.  This visit was not only a moment of profound spiritual significance but also a powerful testament to the enduring bonds of faith, tradition, and unity that transcend borders. We were truly inspired by His All-Holiness’s wisdom, humility, and unwavering commitment to peace and interfaith dialogue. May his visit strengthen the ties that bind us and illuminate the path toward greater understanding and harmony across our communities.

My SCORE Act represents a major step forward in ensuring student-athletes are treated fairly, protected, and fully supported—both on and off the field.  By establishing clear rights related to Name, Image, and Likeness(NIL), health benefits, and academic support, this legislation brings long-overdue structure, accountability, and transparency to college athletics.  It strikes a smart, balanced approach—protecting non-revenue, Olympic, and women’s sports; preserving educational priorities; and reinforcing accountability/transparency—all while creating a consistent national standard that eliminates the patchwork of conflicting state laws.https://t.co/IoJR2WTtDb

The One Big Beautiful Bill makes generational investments in America! Exposure to toxic emissions from burn pits has had tragic consequences for too many members of our military community. We owe it to our heroes to transition to safer, more sustainable waste management technologies— which is why I introduced the WIPE Act. We have a moral obligation to protect public health, reduce environmental harm, and honor those affected by outdated and hazardous disposal practices. This bipartisan bill is a crucial step toward fulfilling that responsibility and safeguarding our service members’ well-being. #WIPEAct #ProtectOurHeroes #MilitaryHealth #BurnPitAwareness #SustainableSolutions

September is Childhood Cancer Awareness Month. This month, we shine a light on the brave children fighting cancer, honor those we've lost, and support the families and medical teams standing beside them.  Only 4% of federal cancer research funding goes to childhood cancers — and that’s not enough. Together, we can raise awareness, push for better treatments, and bring hope to the youngest fighters among us.  As Co-Chair of the Congressional Rare Disease Caucus, I’m fighting for reauthorization of the Pediatric Disease Priority Review Voucher – a program with proven results to create cures for pediatric cancer.  I urge my colleagues to join me in this fight. Let’s turn awareness into action.    #ChildhoodCancerAwareness #FightLikeAKid #HopeForKids

Last month, my colleague and I urged the Department of Commerce to investigate Spain’s troubling decision to partner with Huawei—a company with deep ties to the Chinese Communist Party—to store sensitive judicial wiretap data. This posed serious national security risks not just for Spain, but for the U.S. and our allies, with the potential for American data to be indirectly compromised.  I’m relieved to see Spain has now made the right call by canceling this contract. Protecting our communications infrastructure and sensitive information must remain a top priority.

Synthetic opioids, such as fentanyl, lead to nearly 70% of all overdose deaths, as the drug can be deadly in even small doses and is up to 50 times stronger than heroin and 100 times stronger than morphine. In 2022, more than 200 people died from fentanyl and opioid-related overdoses each day – making fentanyl the leading cause of death for Americans under 50 years old.  Fentanyl claims more lives than heart disease, cancer, suicide, and homicide.  If the temporary order scheduling fentanyl related substances (FRS) ends, several FRS will become street-legal, law enforcement will lose authority to seize them, and drug traffickers will continue to funnel increasingly deadly drugs into the United States.  

This week, I proudly voted in support of the HALT Fentanyl Act, which permanently classifies fentanyl-related substances (FRS) in Schedule I of the Controlled Substances Act.  It also ensure law enforcement has the resources needed to keep these drugs off the street and allows for further research of FRS.  We are doing everything in our power to stop fentanyl from claiming more American lives – everyone should support our efforts to halt this deadly crisis.  The measure now heads to the President’s desk to be signed into law.

App stores are the gatekeepers to the digital world. These agreements often give apps sweeping access to kids' personal data without meaningful safeguards. A national poll commissioned by Digital Childhood Alliance found that 88% of parents want app stores to require parental approval before minors can download a new app.  We are working to give them that ability.

Week after week, the American people are seeing federal judges issue nationwide injunctions that block President Trump from implementing the America First policy agenda he promised to deliver. We are committed to restoring American Energy Dominance, part of which requires unleashing all safe means of domestic energy production. The “All of the Above” approach includes fracking,  a drilling technology used for extracting oil, natural gas, geothermal energy, or water from deep underground – accounting for two-thirds of the natural gas in the United States and halfof the nation’s oil, and positioning the U.S. as the world's leading producer of natural gas and oil. Despite the large amount of American energy it produces, fracking is under threat, as Democrats continue to attack American energy production.  A study conducted by the EPA under the Obama Administration found that fracking has had no “widespread, systemic impacts on drinking water resources in the United States.”  American energy production through fracking leads to lower energy prices for families and workers, boosts economic growth, and improves quality of life for Americans. The Protecting American Energy Production Act prevents a moratorium on hydraulic fracking and clarifies that states have primacy over energy production on state and private land.
